                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300708-129-victim909 t18300708-129-viclabel738"></join>. The prisoner was my <rs id="t18300708-129-deflabel740" type="occupation">bar-man</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300708-129-defend908 t18300708-129-deflabel740"></join> - at nine o'clock in the morning, of the 3rd of July, I took the money out of the till, and placed 1l. worth of marked silver in it; I left him alone in the bar for a quarter of an hour, during which time he was taking money from the customers - I found 1l. 2s. in the till; I called him aside and accused him of taking money from the till - he strongly denied it, but after taxing him particularly, he acknowledged taking it, but said he replaced it with two half-crowns; I said there were no half-crowns in the till - he then said he was sorry, and it was his first offence; he produced twenty-two shillings from his pocket, and among it I found six marked shillings - the other fourteen marked shillings were still in the till; my customers are not here.</p>
